              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Two sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> are said to be <html:em><html:strong>isomorphic</html:strong></html:em> (and have the <html:em><html:strong>same cardinality</html:strong></html:em>) whenever there is a <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them. In this case, we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\cong  B]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/jonmsterling/" title="Jon Sterling" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling/" display-uri="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="/marcelofiore/" title="Marcelo Fiore" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/marcelofiore/" display-uri="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L1/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>jms-00L1</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/jms-00L1/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Examples of isomorphic sets">Examples of <fr:link href="/jms-00L0/" title="Isomorphic sets" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L0/" display-uri="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic sets</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between finite sets is just a “relabeling” of its elements: for example, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{0,1\right \}\mathclose {}}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{\mathsf {false},\mathsf {true}\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Isomorphism of infinite sets can be more confusing: for example, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{n:\mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,n>0\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {N}\times \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and even <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}\right )\mathclose {}}\cong \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/jonmsterling/" title="Jon Sterling" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling/" display-uri="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L2/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>jms-00L2</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/jms-00L2/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Which bijection?">Which <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>?</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Although we are speaking of “being isomorphic” as the property of there being a <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them, in practice, it is almost <html:em>never</html:em> useful to know that there exists some undetermined <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between given sets; it is always important to know <html:em>which</html:em> <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>. Indeed, we have seen in <fr:link href="/jms-00KT/" title="Counting bijections between finite sets" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KT/" display-uri="jms-00KT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KT/" display-uri="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that there can be many distinct <fr:link href="/jms-00KR/" title="Bijection" uri="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR/" display-uri="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link> between two sets.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
